==Worth noting==
It appears the error in ''Conway's'' as to the ship's name in Haitian service ultimately stems from the 1918 edition of ''Jane's Fighting Ships'' (<small>or as some have called it, ''Jane's Frightening Slips''</small>), according to [http://books.google.com/books?ei=xns1VMbYO-mBsQTwmoKYCA&id=lQtHAQAAIAAJ&dq=haiti+cruiser+ferrier&focus=searchwithinvolume&q=umbria this edition of ''Warship International''] But contemporary sources (for instance [http://books.google.com/books?id=_T4ZAAAAYAAJ&pg=PA602&dq=haiti+cruiser+ferrier&hl=en&sa=X&ei=xns1VMbYO-mBsQTwmoKYCA&ved=0CDcQ6AEwAQ#v=onepage&q=haiti%20cruiser%20ferrier&f=false this]) confirm that ''Ferrier'' was in fact the yacht ''America'', which had been purchased by Haiti but never actually put into service owing to a lack of funds. Contemporary newspapers and other sources confirm the ship's name as ''Consul Gostrück''. [[User:Parsecboy|Parsecboy]] ([[User talk:Parsecboy|talk]]) 18:33, 8 October 2014 (UTC)

